## High-Level Migration Overview

On Friday evening, after the agreed cut-off time, we will place the relevant databases into a read-only state and make the SharePoint sites unavailable by stopping the required services. This ensures that no further user changes can be made once the migration window begins.

Once the environment is locked down, we will take the final copy of the required SharePoint content databases. These databases will then be copied to the new environment, mounted, and upgraded to SharePoint Subscription Edition.

After the upgrade is complete, we will start the required SharePoint services and perform initial validation to confirm that the sites are loading correctly and that the upgraded content is being served as expected.

We will then repeat the same process for the Nintex database. The Nintex database will be attached and validated, but the Nintex email service will remain disabled until all required checks have been completed. This is to prevent any unintended workflow emails from being sent during validation.

As part of the cutover, some web application reconfiguration will also be required so that the new SharePoint Subscription Edition environment can be made available using the same URL as the existing SharePoint environment.

We will also need to confirm that a new SPN is configured for the new SharePoint server so that authentication works correctly for the new web application using the existing SharePoint URL.

## Access to the Old SharePoint Farm

One point that should be discussed is whether access to the old SharePoint farm is required after the upgrade.

The US team has advised that they do not provide access to the old SharePoint farm after an upgrade, and this was not offered as part of their upgrade approach. Based on that, we may need to consider whether maintaining access to the old farm is necessary, or whether it introduces additional complexity that we should avoid.

This should be left open for discussion before the final cutover approach is agreed.
